WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.920
Hi everyone. My name is Danielle Smalls-Perkins. And my name is Dorris Scott. And we are the

00:00:14.920 --> 00:00:20.040
co-founders of Mi-R Community. Today, during this lighting talk, we're going to reflect

00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:25.360
a little bit on Mi-R Community this past year and also invite you to join some of the efforts

00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:31.840
that we plan to carry out in the next year. I'll first start with the hope for Mi-R. So

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:36.639
the hope for Mi-R is to promote the visibility and leadership of our users from marginalized

00:00:36.639 --> 00:00:42.480
races, genders, the LGBTQ community, and the disabled community through community led efforts

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:48.439
that support professional development. Right now, we have slightly under 200 members and

00:00:48.439 --> 00:00:54.680
allies within our community Slack from different countries, backgrounds, experiences, and all

00:00:54.680 --> 00:01:01.560
flavors of data people, data scientists, data analysts, etc. All these folks are willing

00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:07.400
to share their unique perspectives and their love of R. So some of the highlights from

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:12.599
this past year really, first, of course, is just getting the group off the ground and

00:01:12.599 --> 00:01:20.320
starting to see people roll in. We started right as the pandemic hit the entire world

00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:28.720
and try to garner support and momentum just as the U.S. was going through a racial reckoning

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:36.120
excuse me, a racial reckoning for racial justice. So to see the outpouring of support, Allison

00:01:36.120 --> 00:01:43.120
Horst designed logo and graphics for us to see other members join and support each other

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:48.879
and lead new initiatives. That's just been truly special. Another huge highlight of this

00:01:48.879 --> 00:01:56.800
past year were the webinars held by our community members. So Dan Ramson led a webinar focused

00:01:56.800 --> 00:02:01.360
on some of the new features in the recently updated dplyr and then some of his favorite

00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:10.320
functions associated with that library. Also, Shell Karuki provided a webinar focused on

00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:17.679
g2plot2 and shared some of her tips and tricks when doing data visualization. We also had

00:02:17.679 --> 00:02:24.240
an RStudio instructor certification panel led by Greg Wilson, Shell Karuki, Janina,

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:29.919
Bellini, Sabine, in which they talked about the process to become an RStudio certified

00:02:29.919 --> 00:02:36.559
instructor and we've also been having some study sessions every month for those that

00:02:36.559 --> 00:02:43.000
are preparing to take the exam to become an RStudio certified instructor. So those are

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:51.880
some of the top highlights. I will now pass it to Doris to share a couple more reflections.

00:02:51.880 --> 00:02:58.520
I have a lot of reflections on how our first year went as an organization, but for the

00:02:58.520 --> 00:03:05.720
sake of time, I will just share only one reflection. We originally created MyR because we wanted

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:10.080
to create a space in which people who did not see themselves in the data science community

00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:17.119
could come together. We hoped that MyR would extend past our ability to adequately support

00:03:17.119 --> 00:03:22.600
all of the intersectional backgrounds that are in the community, and indeed it has. We

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:29.039
are so grateful for members of our community who provide their unique perspectives, insights,

00:03:29.039 --> 00:03:35.679
knowledge, and skills. Thank you so much for all that you bring to our community. In 2021,

00:03:35.679 --> 00:03:40.559
we are working on several endeavors. We don't want to give away our full lineup, so here's

00:03:40.559 --> 00:03:46.399
a preview of what's to come. We are currently working on endeavors to ensure that MyR webinars

00:03:46.399 --> 00:03:52.300
are accessible to MyR members with disabilities, along with the wider community of R users

00:03:52.300 --> 00:03:57.240
with disabilities, and we are working on a Tidy Tuesday event in which we will focus

00:03:57.240 --> 00:04:02.919
on best practices to make our visualizations more accessible. In addition, we intend to

00:04:02.919 --> 00:04:08.759
have more professional development workshops, such as resume workshops and interview preparedness,

00:04:08.759 --> 00:04:16.119
along with a digital security webinar for researchers sharing their work with the public.

00:04:16.119 --> 00:04:22.119
So if you identify as an underrepresented R user, then we invite you to join MyR community

00:04:22.119 --> 00:04:26.519
as a member, and if you'd like to support the community but don't necessarily identify

00:04:26.519 --> 00:04:32.799
as an underrepresented R user, then we would love to have you join as an ally in support

00:04:32.799 --> 00:04:39.279
of the members. You can find us on Twitter and YouTube at MyR community, and you can

00:04:39.279 --> 00:04:46.600
also visit us at www.myrcommunity.com. Thanks so much for listening to our talk.

00:04:46.600 --> 00:04:47.079
Thank you.

